# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: physical-chemistry
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-potential] In thermodynamics, the **chemical potential** of a species is the energy that can be absorbed or released due to a change of the particle number of the given species, e.g. in a chemical reaction or phase transition.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-potential] The chemical potential of a species in a mixture is defined as the rate of change of free energy of a thermodynamic system with respect to the change in the number of atoms or molecules of the species that are added to the system.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-potential] Thus, it is the partial derivative of the free energy with respect to the amount of the species, all other species' concentrations in the mixture remaining constant.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-potential] When both temperature and pressure are held constant, and the number of particles is expressed in moles, the chemical potential is the **partial molar Gibbs free energy**.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-potential] At chemical equilibrium or in phase equilibrium, the total sum of the product of chemical potentials and stoichiometric coefficients is zero, as the free energy is at a minimum.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-potential] In a system in diffusion equilibrium, the chemical potential of any chemical species is uniformly the same everywhere throughout the system.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-potential] In semiconductor physics, the chemical potential of a system of electrons is known as the Fermi level.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-potential] Particles tend to move from higher chemical potential to lower chemical potential because this reduces the free energy.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-potential] In this way, chemical potential is a generalization of "potentials" in physics such as gravitational potential.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-potential] When a ball rolls down a hill, it is moving from a higher gravitational potential (higher internal energy thus higher potential for work) to a lower gravitational potential (lower internal energy).
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-potential] In the same way, as molecules move, react, dissolve, melt, etc., they will always tend naturally to go from a higher chemical potential to a lower one, changing the particle number, which is the conjugate variable to chemical potential.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-potential] A simple example is a system of dilute molecules diffusing in a homogeneous environment.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-potential] In this system, the molecules tend to move from areas with high concentration to low concentration, until eventually, the concentration is the same everywhere.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-potential] The microscopic explanation for this is based on kinetic theory and the random motion of molecules.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-potential] However, it is simpler to describe the process in terms of chemical potentials: For a given temperature, a molecule has a higher chemical potential in a higher-concentration area and a lower chemical potential in a low concentration area.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-potential] Movement of molecules from higher chemical potential to lower chemical potential is accompanied by a release of free energy.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-potential] Another example, not based on concentration but on phase, is an ice cube on a plate above 0 °C.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-potential] An H2O molecule that is in the solid phase (ice) has a higher chemical potential than a water molecule that is in the liquid phase (water) above 0 °C.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-potential] When some of the ice melts, H2O molecules convert from solid to the warmer liquid where their chemical potential is lower, so the ice cube shrinks.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-potential] At the temperature of the melting point, 0 °C, the chemical potentials in water and ice are the same; the ice cube neither grows nor shrinks, and the system is in equilibrium.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-potential] When acid molecules dissociate, the concentration of the undissociated acid molecules (HA) decreases and the concentrations of the product ions (H+ and A−) increase.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-potential] Thus the chemical potential of HA decreases and the sum of the chemical potentials of H+ and A− increases.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-potential] When the sums of chemical potential of reactants and products are equal the system is at equilibrium and there is no tendency for the reaction to proceed in either the forward or backward direction.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-potential] This explains why vinegar is acidic, because acetic acid dissociates to some extent, releasing hydrogen ions into the solution.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-potential] Chemical potentials are important in many aspects of multi-phase equilibrium chemistry, including melting, boiling, evaporation, solubility, osmosis, partition coefficient, liquid-liquid extraction and chromatography.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-potential] In each case the chemical potential of a given species at equilibrium is the same in all phases of the system.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-potential] In electrochemistry, ions do *not* always tend to go from higher to lower chemical potential, but they *do* always go from higher to lower *electrochemical potential*.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-potential] The electrochemical potential completely characterizes all of the influences on an ion's motion, while the chemical potential includes everything *except* the electric force.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-potential] The chemical potential *μ**i* of species *i* (atomic, molecular or nuclear) is defined, as all intensive quantities are, by the phenomenological fundamental equation of thermodynamics.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-potential] *T* is absolute temperature, *S* is entropy, *P* is pressure, and *V* is volume.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-potential] Other work terms, such as those involving electric, magnetic or gravitational fields may be added.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-potential] This expression of the chemical potential as a partial derivative of *U* with respect to the corresponding species particle number is inconvenient for condensed-matter systems, such as chemical solutions, as it is hard to control the volume and entropy to be constant while particles are added.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-potential] A more convenient expression may be obtained by making a Legendre transformation to another thermodynamic potential: the Gibbs free energy $G=U+PV-TS$ .
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-potential] In thermodynamic equilibrium, when the system concerned is at constant temperature and pressure but can exchange particles with its external environment, the Gibbs free energy is at its minimum for the system, that is $\mathrm {d} G=0$ .
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-potential] Use of this equality provides the means to establish the equilibrium constant for a chemical reaction.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-potential] These different forms for the chemical potential are all equivalent, meaning that they have the same physical content, and may be useful in different physical situations.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-potential] The Gibbs–Duhem equation is useful because it relates individual chemical potentials.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-potential] where $n_{\text{A}}$ is the number of moles of A and $n_{\text{B}}$ is the number of moles of B.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-potential] Every instance of phase or chemical equilibrium is characterized by a constant.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-potential] For instance, the melting of ice is characterized by a temperature, known as the melting point at which solid and liquid phases are in equilibrium with each other.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-potential] Chemical potentials can be used to explain the slopes of lines on a phase diagram by using the Clapeyron equation, which in turn can be derived from the Gibbs–Duhem equation.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-potential] They are used to explain colligative properties such as melting-point depression by the application of pressure.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-potential] Henry's law for the solute can be derived from Raoult's law for the solvent using chemical potentials.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-potential] Chemical potential was first described by the American engineer, chemist and mathematical physicist Josiah Willard Gibbs.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-potential] Gibbs later noted also that for the purposes of this definition, any chemical element or combination of elements in given proportions may be considered a substance, whether capable or not of existing by itself as a homogeneous body.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-potential] This freedom to choose the boundary of the system allows the chemical potential to be applied to a huge range of systems.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-potential] The term can be used in thermodynamics and physics for any system undergoing change.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-potential] Chemical potential is also referred to as **partial molar Gibbs energy** (see also partial molar property).
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-potential] Chemical potential is measured in units of energy/particle or, equivalently, energy/mole.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-potential] By studying the interactions of homogeneous substances in contact, i.e. bodies, being in composition part solid, part liquid, and part vapor, and by using a three-dimensional volume–entropy–internal energy graph, Gibbs was able to determine three states of equilibrium, i.e.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-potential] "necessarily stable", "neutral", and "unstable", and whether or not changes will ensue.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-potential] In 1876, Gibbs built on this framework by introducing the concept of chemical potential so to take into account chemical reactions and states of bodies that are chemically different from each other.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-potential] In this description, as used by Gibbs, *ε* refers to the internal energy of the body, *η* refers to the entropy of the body, and *ν* is the volume of the body.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-potential] The abstract definition of chemical potential given above—total change in free energy per extra mole of substance—is more specifically called **total chemical potential**.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-potential] If two locations have different total chemical potentials for a species, some of it may be due to potentials associated with "external" force fields (electric potential energy, gravitational potential energy, etc.), while the rest would be due to "internal" factors (density, temperature, etc.).
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-potential] i.e., the external potential is the sum of electric potential, gravitational potential, etc.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-potential] (where *q* and *m* are the charge and mass of the species, *V*ele and *h* are the electric potential and height of the container, respectively, and *g* is the acceleration due to gravity).
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-potential] The internal chemical potential includes everything else besides the external potentials, such as density, temperature, and enthalpy.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-potential] This formalism can be understood by assuming that the total energy of a system, U , is the sum of two parts: an internal energy, $U_{\text{int}}$ , and an external energy due to the interaction of each particle with an external field, $U_{\text{ext}}=N(qV_{\text{ele}}+mgh+\cdots )$ .
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-potential] The definition of chemical potential applied to $U_{\text{int}}+U_{\text{ext}}$ yields the above expression for $\mu _{\text{tot}}$ .
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-potential] The phrase "chemical potential" sometimes means "total chemical potential", but that is not universal.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-potential] In some fields, in particular electrochemistry, semiconductor physics, and solid-state physics, the term "chemical potential" means *internal* chemical potential, while the term electrochemical potential is used to mean *total* chemical potential.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-potential] Electrons in solids have a chemical potential, defined the same way as the chemical potential of a chemical species: The change in free energy when electrons are added or removed from the system.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-potential] In the case of electrons, the chemical potential is usually expressed in energy per particle rather than energy per mole, and the energy per particle is conventionally given in units of electronvolt (eV).
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-potential] Chemical potential plays an especially important role in solid-state physics and is closely related to the concepts of work function, Fermi energy, and Fermi level.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-potential] For example, n-type silicon has a higher internal chemical potential of electrons than p-type silicon.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-potential] In a p–n junction diode at equilibrium the chemical potential (*internal* chemical potential) varies from the p-type to the n-type side, while the total chemical potential (electrochemical potential, or, Fermi level) is constant throughout the diode.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-potential] As described above, when describing chemical potential, one has to say "relative to what".
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-potential] In the case of electrons in semiconductors, internal chemical potential is often specified relative to some convenient point in the band structure, e.g., to the bottom of the conduction band.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-potential] It may also be specified "relative to vacuum", to yield a quantity known as work function, however, work function varies from surface to surface even on a completely homogeneous material.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-potential] Total chemical potential, on the other hand, is usually specified relative to electrical ground.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-potential] In atomic physics, the chemical potential of the electrons in an atom is sometimes said to be the negative of the atom's electronegativity.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-potential] Likewise, the process of chemical potential equalization is sometimes referred to as the process of electronegativity equalization.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-potential] This connection comes from the Mulliken electronegativity scale.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-potential] In recent years, thermal physics has applied the definition of chemical potential to systems in particle physics and its associated processes.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-potential] For example, in a quark–gluon plasma or other QCD matter, at every point in space there is a chemical potential for photons, a chemical potential for electrons, a chemical potential for baryon number, electric charge, and so forth.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-potential] In the case of photons, photons are bosons and can very easily and rapidly appear or disappear.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-potential] Therefore, at thermodynamic equilibrium, the chemical potential of photons is in most physical situations always and everywhere zero.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-potential] Since this process occurs extremely rapidly - at least, it occurs rapidly in the presence of dense charged matter or also in the walls of the textbook example for a photon gas of blackbody radiation - it is safe to assume that the photon chemical potential here is never different from zero.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-potential] A physical situation where the chemical potential for photons can differ from zero are material-filled optical microcavities, with spacings between cavity mirrors in the wavelength regime.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-potential] In such two-dimensional cases, photon gases with tuneable chemical potential, much reminiscent to gases of material particles, can be observed.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-potential] Electric charge is different because it is intrinsically conserved, i.e. it can be neither created nor destroyed.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-potential] The "chemical potential of electric charge" controls this diffusion: Electric charge, like anything else, will tend to diffuse from areas of higher chemical potential to areas of lower chemical potential.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-potential] Other conserved quantities like baryon number are the same.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-potential] In fact, each conserved quantity is associated with a chemical potential and a corresponding tendency to diffuse to equalize it out.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-potential] In the case of electrons, the behaviour depends on temperature and context.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-potential] At low temperatures, with no positrons present, electrons cannot be created or destroyed.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-potential] Therefore, there is an electron chemical potential that might vary in space, causing diffusion.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-potential] At very high temperatures, however, electrons and positrons can spontaneously appear out of the vacuum (pair production), so the chemical potential of electrons by themselves becomes a less useful quantity than the chemical potential of the conserved quantities like (electrons minus positrons).
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-potential] The chemical potentials of bosons and fermions is related to the number of particles and the temperature by Bose–Einstein statistics and Fermi–Dirac statistics respectively.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-potential] In a mixture or solution, the chemical potential of a substance i depends strongly on its relative concentration, which is usually quantified by mole fraction $x_{i}$ .
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-potential] is the chemical potential of the pure substance.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-potential] The adjacent figure shows the dependence of $\mu _{i}$ on $x_{i}$ for various hypothetical substances, where a logarithmic scale is used for $x_{i}$ (so the above limiting forms appear as straight lines).
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-potential] The dashed lines show, for each case, one of the two limiting forms stated above.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-potential] Note that for the special case of an ideal mixture (ideal solution), the chemical potential is exactly $\mu _{i}(1)+RT\ln(x_{i})$ over the entire range, and $\mu _{i}^{\infty }=\mu _{i}(1)$ .
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-potential] In the case of solutes, the dilute logarithmic ideal may be written instead in terms of molarity, molality, vapor pressure, mass fraction, or others, instead of mole fraction.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-potential] Which choice is made will necessarily influence the values of the $\mu _{i}^{\infty }$ offset, the activity, and the activity coefficient, which may cause some confusion.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-thermodynamics] The structure of chemical thermodynamics is based on the first two laws of thermodynamics.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-thermodynamics] Starting from the first and second laws of thermodynamics, four equations called the "fundamental equations of Gibbs" can be derived.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-thermodynamics] From these four, a multitude of equations, relating the thermodynamic properties of the thermodynamic system can be derived using relatively simple mathematics.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-thermodynamics] This outlines the mathematical framework of chemical thermodynamics.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-thermodynamics] In 1865, the German physicist Rudolf Clausius, in his *Mechanical Theory of Heat*, suggested that the principles of thermochemistry, e.g. the heat evolved in combustion reactions, could be applied to the principles of thermodynamics.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-thermodynamics] Building on the work of Clausius, between the years 1873-76 the American mathematical physicist Willard Gibbs published a series of three papers, the most famous one being the paper *On the Equilibrium of Heterogeneous Substances*.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-thermodynamics] In these papers, Gibbs showed how the first two laws of thermodynamics could be measured graphically and mathematically to determine both the thermodynamic equilibrium of chemical reactions as well as their tendencies to occur or proceed.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-thermodynamics] Gibbs' collection of papers provided the first unified body of thermodynamic theorems from the principles developed by others, such as Clausius and Sadi Carnot.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-thermodynamics] During the early 20th century, two major publications successfully applied the principles developed by Gibbs to chemical processes and thus established the foundation of the science of chemical thermodynamics.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-thermodynamics] The first was the 1923 textbook *Thermodynamics and the Free Energy of Chemical Substances* by Gilbert N.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-thermodynamics] This book was responsible for supplanting the chemical affinity with the term free energy in the English-speaking world.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-thermodynamics] The second was the 1933 book *Modern Thermodynamics by the methods of Willard Gibbs* written by E.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-thermodynamics] In this manner, Lewis, Randall, and Guggenheim are considered as the founders of modern chemical thermodynamics because of the major contribution of these two books in unifying the application of thermodynamics to chemistry.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-thermodynamics] The primary objective of chemical thermodynamics is the establishment of a criterion for determination of the feasibility or spontaneity of a given transformation.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-thermodynamics] Most identities in chemical thermodynamics arise from application of the first and second laws of thermodynamics, particularly the law of conservation of energy, to these state functions.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-thermodynamics] In any spontaneous process, there is always an increase in entropy of the universe.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-thermodynamics] The entropy of a perfect crystal (well ordered) at 0 Kelvin is zero.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-thermodynamics] Energy released (or absorbed) because of a reaction between chemical substances ("reactants") is equal to the difference between the energy content of the products and the reactants.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-thermodynamics] This change in energy is called the change in internal energy of a chemical system.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-thermodynamics] The change in internal energy is equal to the heat change if it is measured under conditions of constant volume (at STP condition), as in a closed rigid container such as a bomb calorimeter.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-thermodynamics] However, at constant pressure, as in reactions in vessels open to the atmosphere, the measured heat is usually not equal to the internal energy change, because pressure-volume work also releases or absorbs energy.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-thermodynamics] A related term is the heat of combustion, which is the chemical energy released due to a combustion reaction and of interest in the study of fuels.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-thermodynamics] Food is similar to hydrocarbon and carbohydrate fuels, and when it is oxidized, its energy release is similar (though assessed differently than for a hydrocarbon fuel — see food energy).
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-thermodynamics] In chemical thermodynamics, the term used for the chemical potential energy is chemical potential, and sometimes the Gibbs-Duhem equation is used.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-thermodynamics] Even for homogeneous "bulk" systems, the free-energy functions depend on the composition, as do all the extensive thermodynamic potentials, including the internal energy.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-thermodynamics] If the quantities { *N**i* }, the number of chemical species, are omitted from the formulae, it is impossible to describe compositional changes.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-thermodynamics] For an unstructured, homogeneous "bulk" system, there are still various *extensive* compositional variables { *N**i* } that *G* depends on, which specify the composition (the amounts of each chemical substance, expressed as the numbers of molecules present or the numbers of moles).
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-thermodynamics] While this formulation is mathematically defensible, it is not particularly transparent since one does not simply add or remove molecules from a system.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-thermodynamics] There is always a *process* involved in changing the composition; e.g., a chemical reaction (or many), or movement of molecules from one phase (liquid) to another (gas or solid).
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-thermodynamics] We should find a notation which does not seem to imply that the amounts of the components ( *N**i* ) can be changed independently.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-thermodynamics] All real processes obey conservation of mass, and in addition, conservation of the numbers of atoms of each kind.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-thermodynamics] Consequently, we introduce an explicit variable to represent the degree of advancement of a process, a progress variable *ξ* for the *extent of reaction* (Prigogine & Defay, p.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-thermodynamics] 37.62), and to the use of the partial derivative ∂*G*/∂*ξ* (in place of the widely used "Δ*G*", since the quantity at issue is not a finite change).
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-thermodynamics] The result is an understandable expression for the dependence of d*G* on chemical reactions (or other processes).
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-thermodynamics] where we introduce a concise and historical name for this quantity, the "affinity", symbolized by **A**, as introduced by Théophile de Donder in 1923.(De Donder; Progogine & Defay, p.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-thermodynamics] 37, 240) The minus sign ensures that in a spontaneous change, when the change in the Gibbs free energy of the process is negative, the chemical species have a positive affinity for each other.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-thermodynamics] with a set of reaction coordinates { ξ*j* }, avoiding the notion that the amounts of the components ( *N**i* ) can be changed independently.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-thermodynamics] The expressions above are equal to zero at thermodynamic equilibrium, while they are negative when chemical reactions proceed at a finite rate, producing entropy.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-thermodynamics] This can be made even more explicit by introducing the reaction *rates* d*ξ**j*/d*t*.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-thermodynamics] For every *physically independent* *process* (Prigogine & Defay, p.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-thermodynamics] This is a remarkable result since the chemical potentials are intensive system variables, depending only on the local molecular milieu.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-thermodynamics] They cannot "know" whether temperature and pressure (or any other system variables) are going to be held constant over time.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-thermodynamics] It is a purely local criterion and must hold regardless of any such constraints.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-thermodynamics] Of course, it could have been obtained by taking partial derivatives of any of the other fundamental state functions, but nonetheless is a general criterion for (−*T* times) the entropy production from that spontaneous process; or at least any part of it that is not captured as external work.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-thermodynamics] We now relax the requirement of a homogeneous "bulk" system by letting the chemical potentials and the affinity apply to any locality in which a chemical reaction (or any other process) is occurring.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-thermodynamics] Any decrease in the Gibbs function of a system is the upper limit for any isothermal, isobaric work that can be captured in the surroundings, or it may simply be dissipated, appearing as *T* times a corresponding increase in the entropy of the system and its surrounding.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-thermodynamics] Or it may go partly toward doing external work and partly toward creating entropy.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-thermodynamics] The important point is that the *extent of reaction* for a chemical reaction may be coupled to the displacement of some external mechanical or electrical quantity in such a way that one can advance only if the other also does.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-thermodynamics] The coupling may occasionally be *rigid*, but it is often flexible and variable.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-thermodynamics] The assertion that all *spontaneous reactions have a negative ΔG* is merely a restatement of the second law of thermodynamics, giving it the physical dimensions of energy and somewhat obscuring its significance in terms of entropy.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-thermodynamics] When no useful work is being done, it would be less misleading to use the Legendre transforms of the entropy appropriate for constant *T*, or for constant *T* and *P*, the Massieu functions −*F*/*T* and −*G*/*T*, respectively.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-thermodynamics] Generally the systems treated with the conventional chemical thermodynamics are either at equilibrium or near equilibrium.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-thermodynamics] Ilya Prigogine developed the thermodynamic treatment of open systems that are far from equilibrium.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-thermodynamics] In doing so he has discovered phenomena and structures of completely new and completely unexpected types.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-thermodynamics] His generalized, nonlinear and irreversible thermodynamics has found surprising applications in a wide variety of fields.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-thermodynamics] The non-equilibrium thermodynamics has been applied for explaining how ordered structures e.g. the biological systems, can develop from disorder.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-thermodynamics] Even if Onsager's relations are utilized, the classical principles of equilibrium in thermodynamics still show that linear systems close to equilibrium always develop into states of disorder which are stable to perturbations and cannot explain the occurrence of ordered structures.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-thermodynamics] Prigogine called these systems dissipative systems, because they are formed and maintained by the dissipative processes which take place because of the exchange of energy between the system and its environment and because they disappear if that exchange ceases.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-thermodynamics] They may be said to live in symbiosis with their environment.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-thermodynamics] The method which Prigogine used to study the stability of the dissipative structures to perturbations is of very great general interest.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-thermodynamics] It makes it possible to study the most varied problems, such as city traffic problems, the stability of insect communities, the development of ordered biological structures and the growth of cancer cells to mention but a few examples.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-thermodynamics] In this regard, it is crucial to understand the role of walls and other *constraints*, and the distinction between *independent* processes and *coupling*.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-thermodynamics] Contrary to the clear implications of many reference sources, the previous analysis is not restricted to homogeneous, isotropic bulk systems which can deliver only *P*d*V* work to the outside world, but applies even to the most structured systems.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-thermodynamics] There are complex systems with many chemical "reactions" going on at the same time, some of which are really only parts of the same, overall process.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-thermodynamics] An *independent* process is one that *could* proceed even if all others were unaccountably stopped in their tracks.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-thermodynamics] Understanding this is perhaps a "thought experiment" in chemical kinetics, but actual examples exist.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-thermodynamics] A gas-phase reaction at constant temperature and pressure which results in an increase in the number of molecules will lead to an increase in volume.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-thermodynamics] Inside a cylinder closed with a piston, it can proceed only by doing work on the piston.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-thermodynamics] The extent variable for the reaction can increase only if the piston moves out, and conversely if the piston is pushed inward, the reaction is driven backwards.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-thermodynamics] Similarly, a redox reaction might occur in an electrochemical cell with the passage of current through a wire connecting the electrodes.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-thermodynamics] The half-cell reactions at the electrodes are constrained if no current is allowed to flow.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-thermodynamics] The current might be dissipated as Joule heating, or it might in turn run an electrical device like a motor doing mechanical work.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-thermodynamics] An automobile lead-acid battery can be recharged, driving the chemical reaction backwards.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-thermodynamics] In this case as well, the reaction is not an independent process.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-thermodynamics] Some, perhaps most, of the Gibbs free energy of reaction may be delivered as external work.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-thermodynamics] The hydrolysis of ATP to ADP and phosphate can drive the force-times-distance work delivered by living muscles, and synthesis of ATP is in turn driven by a redox chain in mitochondria and chloroplasts, which involves the transport of ions across the membranes of these cellular organelles.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-thermodynamics] The coupling of processes here, and in the previous examples, is often not complete.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-thermodynamics] Gas can leak slowly past a piston, just as it can slowly leak out of a rubber balloon.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-thermodynamics] Some reaction may occur in a battery even if no external current is flowing.
[src:physical-chemistry/chemical-thermodynamics] There is usually a coupling coefficient, which may depend on relative rates, which determines what percentage of the driving free energy is turned into external work, or captured as "chemical work", a misnomer for the free energy of another chemical process.
[src:physical-chemistry/colligative-properties] In chemistry, **colligative properties** are those properties of solutions that depend on the ratio of the number of solute particles to the number of solvent particles in a solution, and not on the nature of the chemical species present.
[src:physical-chemistry/colligative-properties] The number ratio can be related to the various units for concentration of a solution such as molarity, molality, normality, etc.
[src:physical-chemistry/colligative-properties] The assumption that solution properties are independent of nature of solute particles is exact only for ideal solutions, which are solutions that exhibit thermodynamic properties analogous to those of an ideal gas, and is approximate for dilute real solutions.
[src:physical-chemistry/colligative-properties] In other words, colligative properties are a set of solution properties that can be reasonably approximated by the assumption that the solution is ideal.
[src:physical-chemistry/colligative-properties] Only properties which result from the dissolution of a nonvolatile solute in a volatile liquid solvent are considered.
[src:physical-chemistry/colligative-properties] They are essentially solvent properties which are changed by the presence of the solute.
[src:physical-chemistry/colligative-properties] The solute particles displace some solvent molecules in the liquid phase and thereby reduce the concentration of solvent and increase its entropy, so that the colligative properties are independent of the nature of the solute.
[src:physical-chemistry/colligative-properties] The word colligative is derived from the Latin *colligatus* meaning *bound together*.
[src:physical-chemistry/colligative-properties] This indicates that all colligative properties have a common feature, namely that they are related only to the number of solute molecules relative to the number of solvent molecules and not to the nature of the solute.
[src:physical-chemistry/colligative-properties] For a given solute-solvent mass ratio, all colligative properties are inversely proportional to solute molar mass.
[src:physical-chemistry/colligative-properties] Measurement of colligative properties for a dilute solution of a non-ionized solute such as urea or glucose in water or another solvent can lead to determinations of relative molar masses, both for small molecules and for polymers which cannot be studied by other means.
[src:physical-chemistry/colligative-properties] Alternatively, measurements for ionized solutes can lead to an estimation of the percentage of dissociation taking place.
[src:physical-chemistry/colligative-properties] Colligative properties are studied mostly for dilute solutions, whose behavior may be approximated as that of an ideal solution.
[src:physical-chemistry/colligative-properties] In fact, all of the properties listed above are colligative only in the dilute limit: at higher concentrations, the freezing point depression, boiling point elevation, vapor pressure elevation or depression, and osmotic pressure are all dependent on the chemical nature of the solvent and the solute.
[src:physical-chemistry/colligative-properties] A vapor is a substance in a gaseous state at a temperature lower than its critical point.
[src:physical-chemistry/colligative-properties] Vapor pressure is the pressure exerted by a vapor in thermodynamic equilibrium with its solid or liquid state.
[src:physical-chemistry/colligative-properties] The vapor pressure of a solvent is lowered when a non-volatile solute is dissolved in it to form a solution.
[src:physical-chemistry/colligative-properties] The vapor pressure *lowering* relative to pure solvent is $\Delta p=p_{\rm {A}}^{\star }-p=p_{\rm {A}}^{\star }(1-x_{\rm {A}})=p_{\rm {A}}^{\star }x_{\rm {B}}$ , which is proportional to the mole fraction of solute.
[src:physical-chemistry/colligative-properties] If the solute dissociates in solution, then the number of moles of solute is increased by the van 't Hoff factor i , which represents the true number of solute particles for each formula unit.
[src:physical-chemistry/colligative-properties] The measured colligative properties show that *i* is somewhat less than 3 due to ion association.
[src:physical-chemistry/colligative-properties] Addition of solute to form a solution stabilizes the solvent in the liquid phase, and lowers the solvent's chemical potential so that solvent molecules have less tendency to move to the gas or solid phases.
[src:physical-chemistry/colligative-properties] As a result, liquid solutions slightly above the solvent boiling point at a given pressure become stable, which means that the boiling point increases.
[src:physical-chemistry/colligative-properties] Similarly, liquid solutions slightly below the solvent freezing point become stable meaning that the freezing point decreases.
[src:physical-chemistry/colligative-properties] Both the boiling point elevation and the freezing point depression are proportional to the lowering of vapor pressure in a dilute solution.
[src:physical-chemistry/colligative-properties] These properties are colligative in systems where the solute is essentially confined to the liquid phase.
[src:physical-chemistry/colligative-properties] Boiling point elevation (like vapor pressure lowering) is colligative for non-volatile solutes where the solute presence in the gas phase is negligible.
[src:physical-chemistry/colligative-properties] Freezing point depression is colligative for most solutes since very few solutes dissolve appreciably in solid solvents.
[src:physical-chemistry/colligative-properties] The boiling point of a liquid at a given external pressure is the temperature ( $T_{\rm {b}}$ ) at which the vapor pressure of the liquid equals the external pressure.
[src:physical-chemistry/colligative-properties] The *normal boiling point* is the boiling point at a pressure equal to 1 atm.
[src:physical-chemistry/colligative-properties] The boiling point of a pure solvent is increased by the addition of a non-volatile solute, and the elevation can be measured by ebullioscopy.
[src:physical-chemistry/colligative-properties] Here *i* is the van 't Hoff factor as above, *K*b is the ebullioscopic constant of the solvent (equal to 0.512 °C kg/mol for water), and *m* is the molality of the solution.
[src:physical-chemistry/colligative-properties] The boiling point is the temperature at which there is equilibrium between liquid and gas phases.
[src:physical-chemistry/colligative-properties] At the boiling point, the number of gas molecules condensing to liquid equals the number of liquid molecules evaporating to gas.
[src:physical-chemistry/colligative-properties] Adding a solute dilutes the concentration of the liquid molecules and reduces the rate of evaporation.
[src:physical-chemistry/colligative-properties] To compensate for this and re-attain equilibrium, the boiling point occurs at a higher temperature.
[src:physical-chemistry/colligative-properties] If the solution is assumed to be an ideal solution, *K*b can be evaluated from the thermodynamic condition for liquid-vapor equilibrium.
[src:physical-chemistry/colligative-properties] At the boiling point, the chemical potential μA of the solvent in the solution phase equals the chemical potential in the pure vapor phase above the solution.
[src:physical-chemistry/colligative-properties] This leads to the result $K_{b}=RMT_{b}^{2}/\Delta H_{\mathrm {vap} }$ , where R is the molar gas constant, M is the solvent molar mass and Δ*H*vap is the solvent molar enthalpy of vaporization.
[src:physical-chemistry/colligative-properties] The freezing point ( $T_{\rm {f}}$ ) of a pure solvent is lowered by the addition of a solute which is insoluble in the solid solvent, and the measurement of this difference is called *cryoscopy*.
[src:physical-chemistry/colligative-properties] Here *Kf* is the cryoscopic constant (equal to 1.86 °C kg/mol for the freezing point of water), *i* is the van 't Hoff factor, and *m* the molality (in mol/kg).
[src:physical-chemistry/colligative-properties] This predicts the melting of ice by road salt.
[src:physical-chemistry/colligative-properties] In the liquid solution, the solvent is diluted by the addition of a solute, so that fewer molecules are available to freeze.
[src:physical-chemistry/colligative-properties] Re-establishment of equilibrium is achieved at a lower temperature at which the rate of freezing becomes equal to the rate of liquefying.
[src:physical-chemistry/colligative-properties] At the lower freezing point, the vapor pressure of the liquid is equal to the vapor pressure of the corresponding solid, and the chemical potentials of the two phases are equal as well.
[src:physical-chemistry/colligative-properties] The equality of chemical potentials permits the evaluation of the cryoscopic constant as $K_{f}=RMT_{f}^{2}/\Delta _{\mathrm {fus} }H$ , where Δfus*H* is the solvent molar enthalpy of fusion.
[src:physical-chemistry/colligative-properties] The osmotic pressure of a solution is the difference in pressure between the solution and the pure liquid solvent when the two are in equilibrium across a semipermeable membrane, which allows the passage of solvent molecules but not of solute particles.
[src:physical-chemistry/colligative-properties] If the two phases are at the same initial pressure, there is a net transfer of solvent across the membrane into the solution known as osmosis.
[src:physical-chemistry/colligative-properties] The process stops and equilibrium is attained when the pressure difference equals the osmotic pressure.
[src:physical-chemistry/colligative-properties] Two laws governing the osmotic pressure of a dilute solution were discovered by the German botanist W.
[src:physical-chemistry/colligative-properties] The osmotic pressure of a solution is directly proportional to its absolute temperature.
[src:physical-chemistry/colligative-properties] These are analogous to Boyle's law and Charles's law for gases.
[src:physical-chemistry/colligative-properties] The osmotic pressure is proportional to the concentration of solute particles *ci* and is therefore a colligative property.
[src:physical-chemistry/colligative-properties] As with the other colligative properties, this equation is a consequence of the equality of solvent chemical potentials of the two phases in equilibrium.
[src:physical-chemistry/colligative-properties] In this case the phases are the pure solvent at pressure *P* and the solution at total pressure (*P* + $\Pi$ ).
[src:physical-chemistry/colligative-properties] The word colligative (Latin: co, ligare) was introduced in 1891 by Wilhelm Ostwald.
[src:physical-chemistry/colligative-properties] *constitutional* properties, which depend further on the molecular structure of the given solute.
[src:physical-chemistry/fugacity] In thermodynamics, the **fugacity** of a real gas is an effective partial pressure which replaces the ideal partial pressure in an accurate computation of chemical equilibrium.
[src:physical-chemistry/fugacity] It is equal to the pressure of an ideal gas which has the same temperature and molar Gibbs free energy (chemical potential) as the real gas.
[src:physical-chemistry/fugacity] Fugacities are determined experimentally or estimated from various models such as a Van der Waals gas that are closer to reality than an ideal gas.
[src:physical-chemistry/fugacity] For an ideal gas, fugacity and pressure are equal, and so *φ* = 1.
[src:physical-chemistry/fugacity] Taken at the same temperature and pressure, the difference between the molar Gibbs free energies of a real gas and the corresponding ideal gas is equal to *RT* ln *φ*.
[src:physical-chemistry/fugacity] The fugacity is closely related to the thermodynamic activity.
[src:physical-chemistry/fugacity] For a gas, the activity is simply the fugacity divided by a reference pressure to give a dimensionless quantity.
[src:physical-chemistry/fugacity] This reference pressure is called the standard state and normally chosen as 1 atmosphere or 1 bar.
[src:physical-chemistry/fugacity] Accurate calculations of chemical equilibrium for real gases should use the fugacity rather than the pressure.
[src:physical-chemistry/fugacity] The thermodynamic condition for chemical equilibrium is that the total chemical potential of reactants is equal to that of products.
[src:physical-chemistry/fugacity] If the chemical potential of each gas is expressed as a function of fugacity, the equilibrium condition may be transformed into the familiar reaction quotient form (or law of mass action) except that the pressures are replaced by fugacities.
[src:physical-chemistry/fugacity] For a condensed phase (liquid or solid) in equilibrium with its vapor phase, the chemical potential is equal to that of the vapor, and therefore the fugacity is equal to the fugacity of the vapor.
[src:physical-chemistry/fugacity] This fugacity is approximately equal to the vapor pressure when the vapor pressure is not too high.
[src:physical-chemistry/fugacity] Fugacity is closely related to the chemical potential *μ*.
[src:physical-chemistry/fugacity] In a pure substance, *μ* is equal to the Gibbs energy *G*m for a mole of the substance, and $d\mu =dG_{\mathrm {m} }=-S_{\mathrm {m} }dT+V_{\mathrm {m} }dP,$ where *T* and *P* are the temperature and pressure, *V*m is the volume per mole and *S*m is the entropy per mole.
[src:physical-chemistry/fugacity] For an ideal gas the equation of state can be written as $V_{\mathrm {m} }^{\text{ideal}}={\frac {RT}{P}},$ where *R* is the ideal gas constant.
[src:physical-chemistry/fugacity] The differential change of the chemical potential between two states of slightly different pressures but equal temperature (i.e., d*T* = 0) is given by $d\mu =V_{\mathrm {m} }dP=RT\,{\frac {dP}{P}}=RT\,d\ln P,$ where **ln p** is the natural logarithm of p.
[src:physical-chemistry/fugacity] In other words, real gases behave like ideal gases at low pressures and high temperatures.
[src:physical-chemistry/fugacity] At moderately high pressures, attractive interactions between molecules reduce the pressure compared to the ideal gas law; and at very high pressures, the sizes of the molecules are no longer negligible and repulsive forces between molecules increases the pressure.
[src:physical-chemistry/fugacity] At low temperatures, molecules are more likely to stick together instead of rebounding elastically.
[src:physical-chemistry/fugacity] The ideal gas law can still be used to describe the behavior of a real gas if the pressure is replaced by a *fugacity* *f*, defined so that $d\mu =RT\,d\ln f$ and $\lim _{P\to 0}{\frac {f}{P}}=1.$ That is, at low pressures *f* is the same as the pressure, so it has the same units as pressure.
[src:physical-chemistry/fugacity] The ratio $\varphi ={\frac {f}{P}}$ is called the *fugacity coefficient*.
[src:physical-chemistry/fugacity] If a reference state is denoted by a zero superscript, then integrating the equation for the chemical potential gives $\mu -\mu ^{0}=RT\,\ln {\frac {f}{P^{0}}},$ Note this can also be expressed with $a=f/P^{0}$ , a dimensionless quantity, called the *activity*.
[src:physical-chemistry/fugacity] The contribution of nonideality to the molar Gibbs energy of a real gas is equal to *RT* ln *φ*.
[src:physical-chemistry/fugacity] For nitrogen at 100 atm, *G*m = *G*m,id + *RT* ln 0.9703, which is less than the ideal value *G*m,id because of intermolecular attractive forces.
[src:physical-chemistry/fugacity] Finally, the activity is just 97.03 without units.
[src:physical-chemistry/fugacity] When calculating the fugacity of the compressed phase, one can generally assume the volume is constant.
[src:physical-chemistry/fugacity] Using *f*sat = *φ*sat *p*sat, where *φ*sat is the fugacity coefficient, $f=\varphi _{\mathrm {sat} }P_{\mathrm {sat} }\exp \left({\frac {V\left(P-P_{\mathrm {sat} }\right)}{RT}}\right).$ This equation allows the fugacity to be calculated using tabulated values for saturated vapor pressure.
[src:physical-chemistry/fugacity] Often the pressure is low enough for the vapor phase to be considered an ideal gas, so the fugacity coefficient is approximately equal to 1.
[src:physical-chemistry/fugacity] Unless pressures are very high, the Poynting factor is usually small and the exponential term is near 1.
[src:physical-chemistry/fugacity] Frequently, the fugacity of the pure liquid is used as a reference state when defining and using mixture activity coefficients.
[src:physical-chemistry/fugacity] The fugacity is most useful in mixtures.
[src:physical-chemistry/fugacity] It does not add any new information compared to the chemical potential, but it has computational advantages.
[src:physical-chemistry/fugacity] As the molar fraction of a component goes to zero, the chemical potential diverges but the fugacity goes to zero.
[src:physical-chemistry/fugacity] In addition, there are natural reference states for fugacity (for example, an ideal gas makes a natural reference state for gas mixtures since the fugacity and pressure converge at low pressure).
[src:physical-chemistry/fugacity] The partial pressures obey Dalton's law: $P_{i}=y_{i}P,$ where P is the total pressure and *yi* is the mole fraction of the component (so the partial pressures add up to the total pressure).
[src:physical-chemistry/fugacity] The fugacities commonly obey a similar law called the Lewis and Randall rule: $f_{i}=y_{i}f_{i}^{*},$ where *f** *i* is the fugacity that component *i* would have if the entire gas had that composition at the same temperature and pressure.
[src:physical-chemistry/fugacity] Both laws are expressions of an assumption that the gases behave independently.
[src:physical-chemistry/fugacity] In a liquid mixture, the fugacity of each component is equal to that of a vapor component in equilibrium with the liquid.
[src:physical-chemistry/fugacity] In an ideal solution, the fugacities obey the Lewis-Randall rule: $f_{i}=x_{i}f_{i}^{*},$ where *xi* is the mole fraction in the liquid and *f*∗ *i* is the fugacity of the pure liquid phase.
[src:physical-chemistry/fugacity] This is a good approximation when the component molecules have similar size, shape and polarity.
[src:physical-chemistry/fugacity] In a dilute solution with two components, the component with the larger molar fraction (the solvent) may still obey Raoult's law even if the other component (the solute) has different properties.
[src:physical-chemistry/fugacity] That is because its molecules experience essentially the same environment that they do in the absence of the solute.
[src:physical-chemistry/fugacity] By contrast, each solute molecule is surrounded by solvent molecules, so it obeys a different law known as Henry's law.
[src:physical-chemistry/fugacity] By Henry's law, the fugacity of the solute is proportional to its concentration.
[src:physical-chemistry/fugacity] The constant of proportionality (a measured Henry's constant) depends on whether the concentration is represented by the mole fraction, molality or molarity.
[src:physical-chemistry/fugacity] The pressure dependence of fugacity (at constant temperature) is given by $\left({\frac {\partial \ln f}{\partial P}}\right)_{T}={\frac {V_{\mathrm {m} }}{RT}}$ and is always positive.
[src:physical-chemistry/fugacity] The temperature dependence at constant pressure is $\left({\frac {\partial \ln f}{\partial T}}\right)_{P}={\frac {\Delta H_{\mathrm {m} }}{RT^{2}}},$ where Δ*H*m is the change in molar enthalpy as the gas expands, liquid vaporizes, or solid sublimates into a vacuum.
[src:physical-chemistry/fugacity] Also, if the pressure is *P*0, then $\left({\frac {\partial }{\partial T}}\left(T\ln {\frac {f}{P^{0}}}\right)\right)_{P}=-{\frac {S_{\mathrm {m} }}{R}}<0.$ Since the temperature and entropy are positive, ln ⁠*f*/*P*0⁠ decreases with increasing temperature.
[src:physical-chemistry/fugacity] The fugacity can be deduced from measurements of volume as a function of pressure at constant temperature.
[src:physical-chemistry/fugacity] In that case, $\ln \varphi ={\frac {1}{RT}}\int _{0}^{p}\left(V_{m}-V_{\mathrm {m} }^{\mathrm {ideal} }\right)dP.$ This integral can also be calculated using an equation of state.
[src:physical-chemistry/fugacity] Then, to a good approximation, most gases have the same value of *Z* for the same reduced temperature and pressure.
[src:physical-chemistry/fugacity] However, in geochemical applications, this principle ceases to be accurate at pressures where metamorphism occurs.
[src:physical-chemistry/fugacity] For a gas obeying the van der Waals equation, the explicit formula for the fugacity coefficient is $RT\ln \varphi ={\frac {RTb}{V_{\mathrm {m} }-b}}-{\frac {2a}{V_{\mathrm {m} }}}-RT\ln \left(1-{\frac {a(V_{\mathrm {m} }-b)}{RTV_{\mathrm {m} }^{2}}}\right)$ This formula is based on the molar volume.
[src:physical-chemistry/fugacity] Since the pressure and the molar volume are related through the equation of state; a typical procedure would be to choose a volume, calculate the corresponding pressure, and then evaluate the right-hand side of the equation.
[src:physical-chemistry/fugacity] The word *fugacity* is derived from the Latin *fugere*, to flee.
[src:physical-chemistry/fugacity] In the sense of an "escaping tendency", it was introduced to thermodynamics in 1901 by the American chemist Gilbert N.
[src:physical-chemistry/fugacity] Lewis and popularized in an influential textbook by Lewis and Merle Randall, *Thermodynamics and the Free Energy of Chemical Substances*, in 1923.
[src:physical-chemistry/fugacity] The "escaping tendency" referred to the flow of matter between phases and played a similar role to that of temperature in heat flow.
[src:physical-chemistry/fugacity] At the time of Lewis' 1901 paper, physical chemistry was primarily based on inexact gas pressure laws, involving vapor pressures and partial pressures.
[src:physical-chemistry/fugacity] By replacing these gas pressures with fugacity, Lewis preserved these laws’ mathematical simplicity while accounting for real-world deviations.
[src:physical-chemistry/fugacity] Historians argue that Lewis, a young scientist aware of Josiah Willard Gibbs’ rigorous but abstract thermodynamics (including chemical potential), sought to reform the prevailing experimental framework with exact equations that retained practical utility.
[src:physical-chemistry/fugacity] Although Lewis’ 1901 paper omitted Gibbs’ formalism entirely, his later works explicitly linked fugacity to chemical potential.
[src:physical-chemistry/physical-chemistry] Physical chemistry, in contrast to chemical physics, is predominantly (but not always) a supra-molecular science, as the majority of the principles on which it was founded relate to the bulk rather than the molecular or atomic structure alone (for example, chemical equilibrium and colloids).
[src:physical-chemistry/physical-chemistry] Reaction kinetics on the rate of a reaction.
[src:physical-chemistry/physical-chemistry] The identity of ions and the electrical conductivity of materials.
[src:physical-chemistry/physical-chemistry] Surface science and electrochemistry of cell membranes.
[src:physical-chemistry/physical-chemistry] Interaction of one body with another in terms of quantities of heat and work called thermodynamics.
[src:physical-chemistry/physical-chemistry] Study of colligative properties of number of species present in solution.
[src:physical-chemistry/physical-chemistry] Number of phases, number of components and degree of freedom (or variance) can be correlated with one another with help of phase rule.
[src:physical-chemistry/physical-chemistry] Behaviour of microscopic systems using quantum mechanics and macroscopic systems using statistical thermodynamics.
[src:physical-chemistry/physical-chemistry] Calculation of the energy of electron movement in molecules and metal complexes.
[src:physical-chemistry/physical-chemistry] The key concepts of physical chemistry are the ways in which pure physics is applied to chemical problems.
[src:physical-chemistry/physical-chemistry] One of the key concepts in classical chemistry is that all chemical compounds can be described as groups of atoms bonded together and chemical reactions can be described as the making and breaking of those bonds.
[src:physical-chemistry/physical-chemistry] Predicting the properties of chemical compounds from a description of atoms and how they bond is one of the major goals of physical chemistry.
[src:physical-chemistry/physical-chemistry] To describe the atoms and bonds precisely, it is necessary to know both where the nuclei of the atoms are, and how electrons are distributed around them.
[src:physical-chemistry/physical-chemistry] Quantum chemistry, a subfield of physical chemistry especially concerned with the application of quantum mechanics to chemical problems, provides tools to determine how strong and what shape bonds are, how nuclei move, and how light can be absorbed or emitted by a chemical compound.
[src:physical-chemistry/physical-chemistry] Spectroscopy is the related sub-discipline of physical chemistry which is specifically concerned with the interaction of electromagnetic radiation with matter.
[src:physical-chemistry/physical-chemistry] Another set of important questions in chemistry concerns what kind of reactions can happen spontaneously and which properties are possible for a given chemical mixture.
[src:physical-chemistry/physical-chemistry] It can frequently be used to assess whether a reactor or engine design is feasible, or to check the validity of experimental data.
[src:physical-chemistry/physical-chemistry] To a limited extent, quasi-equilibrium and non-equilibrium thermodynamics can describe irreversible changes.
[src:physical-chemistry/physical-chemistry] However, classical thermodynamics is mostly concerned with systems in equilibrium and reversible changes and not what actually does happen, or how fast, away from equilibrium.
[src:physical-chemistry/physical-chemistry] Which reactions do occur and how fast is the subject of chemical kinetics, another branch of physical chemistry.
[src:physical-chemistry/physical-chemistry] A key idea in chemical kinetics is that for reactants to react and form products, most chemical species must go through transition states which are higher in energy than either the reactants or the products and serve as a barrier to reaction.
[src:physical-chemistry/physical-chemistry] In general, the higher the barrier, the slower the reaction.
[src:physical-chemistry/physical-chemistry] A second is that most chemical reactions occur as a sequence of elementary reactions, each with its own transition state.
[src:physical-chemistry/physical-chemistry] Key questions in kinetics include how the rate of reaction depends on temperature and on the concentrations of reactants and catalysts in the reaction mixture, as well as how catalysts and reaction conditions can be engineered to optimize the reaction rate.
[src:physical-chemistry/physical-chemistry] The precise reasons for this are described in statistical mechanics, a specialty within physical chemistry which is also shared with physics.
[src:physical-chemistry/physical-chemistry] Statistical mechanics also provides ways to predict the properties we see in everyday life from molecular properties without relying on empirical correlations based on chemical similarities.
[src:physical-chemistry/physical-chemistry] The term "physical chemistry" was coined by Mikhail Lomonosov in 1752, when he presented a lecture course entitled "A Course in True Physical Chemistry" (Russian: Курс истинной физической химии) before the students of Petersburg University.
[src:physical-chemistry/physical-chemistry] In the preamble to these lectures he gives the definition: "Physical chemistry is the science that must explain under provisions of physical experiments the reason for what is happening in complex bodies through chemical operations".
[src:physical-chemistry/physical-chemistry] Modern physical chemistry originated in the 1860s to 1880s with work on chemical thermodynamics, electrolytes in solutions, chemical kinetics and other subjects.
[src:physical-chemistry/physical-chemistry] One milestone was the publication in 1876 by Josiah Willard Gibbs of his paper, *On the Equilibrium of Heterogeneous Substances*.
[src:physical-chemistry/physical-chemistry] This paper introduced several of the cornerstones of physical chemistry, such as Gibbs energy, chemical potentials, and Gibbs' phase rule.
[src:physical-chemistry/physical-chemistry] The first scientific journal specifically in the field of physical chemistry was the German journal, *Zeitschrift für Physikalische Chemie*, founded in 1887 by Wilhelm Ostwald and Jacobus Henricus van 't Hoff.
[src:physical-chemistry/physical-chemistry] Together with Svante August Arrhenius, these were the leading figures in physical chemistry in the late 19th century and early 20th century.
[src:physical-chemistry/physical-chemistry] All three were awarded the Nobel Prize in Chemistry between 1901 and 1909.
[src:physical-chemistry/physical-chemistry] Developments in the following decades include the application of statistical mechanics to chemical systems and work on colloids and surface chemistry, where Irving Langmuir made many contributions.
[src:physical-chemistry/physical-chemistry] Another important step was the development of quantum mechanics into quantum chemistry from the 1930s, where Linus Pauling was one of the leading names.
[src:physical-chemistry/physical-chemistry] Historical journals that covered both chemistry and physics include *Annales de chimie et de physique* (started in 1789, published under the name given here from 1815 to 1914).
[src:physical-chemistry/reaction-rate] The **reaction rate** or **rate of reaction** is the speed at which a chemical reaction takes place, defined as proportional to the increase in the concentration of a product per unit time and to the decrease in the concentration of a reactant per unit time.
[src:physical-chemistry/reaction-rate] For example, the oxidative rusting of iron under Earth's atmosphere is a slow reaction that can take many years, but the combustion of cellulose in a fire is a reaction that takes place in fractions of a second.
[src:physical-chemistry/reaction-rate] For most reactions, the rate decreases as the reaction proceeds.
[src:physical-chemistry/reaction-rate] A reaction's rate can be determined by measuring the changes in concentration over time.
[src:physical-chemistry/reaction-rate] Chemical kinetics is the part of physical chemistry that concerns how rates of chemical reactions are measured and predicted, and how reaction-rate data can be used to deduce probable reaction mechanisms.
[src:physical-chemistry/reaction-rate] The concepts of chemical kinetics are applied in many disciplines, such as chemical engineering, enzymology and environmental engineering.
[src:physical-chemistry/reaction-rate] The lowercase letters (a, b, p, and q) represent stoichiometric coefficients, while the capital letters represent the reactants (A and B) and the products (P and Q).
[src:physical-chemistry/reaction-rate] The reaction rate thus defined has the units of mol/(L⋅s).
[src:physical-chemistry/reaction-rate] The rate of a reaction is always positive.
[src:physical-chemistry/reaction-rate] A negative sign is present to indicate that the reactant concentration is decreasing.
[src:physical-chemistry/reaction-rate] The IUPAC recommends that the unit of time should always be the second.
[src:physical-chemistry/reaction-rate] The rate of reaction differs from the rate of increase of concentration of a product P by a constant factor (the reciprocal of its stoichiometric number) and for a reactant A by minus the reciprocal of the stoichiometric number.
[src:physical-chemistry/reaction-rate] The stoichiometric numbers are included so that the defined rate is independent of which reactant or product species is chosen for measurement.
[src:physical-chemistry/reaction-rate] For example, if *a* = 1 and *b* = 3, then B is consumed three times more rapidly than A, but $\nu =-{\tfrac {d[\mathrm {A} ]}{dt}}=-{\tfrac {1}{3}}{\tfrac {d[\mathrm {B} ]}{dt}}$ is uniquely defined.
[src:physical-chemistry/reaction-rate] An additional advantage of this definition is that for an elementary and irreversible reaction, $\nu$ is equal to the product of the probability of overcoming the transition state activation energy and the number of times per second the transition state is approached by reactant molecules.
[src:physical-chemistry/reaction-rate] When so defined, for an elementary and irreversible reaction, $\nu$ is the rate of successful chemical reaction events leading to the product.
[src:physical-chemistry/reaction-rate] The above definition is only valid for a *single reaction*, in a *closed system* of *constant volume*.
[src:physical-chemistry/reaction-rate] If water is added to a pot containing salty water, the concentration of salt decreases, although there is no chemical reaction.
[src:physical-chemistry/reaction-rate] When applied to the closed system at constant volume considered previously, this equation reduces to $\nu ={\frac {d[A]}{dt}},$ where the concentration [A] is related to the number of molecules *N*A by $[\mathrm {A} ]={\tfrac {N_{\mathrm {A} }}{N_{0}V}},$ with *N*0 denoting the Avogadro constant.
[src:physical-chemistry/reaction-rate] For a single reaction in a closed system of varying volume, the so-called *rate of conversion* can be used, in order to avoid handling concentrations.
[src:physical-chemistry/reaction-rate] When side products or reaction intermediates are formed, the IUPAC recommends the use of the terms **the rate of increase of concentration** and **rate of the decrease of concentration** for products and reactants respectively.
[src:physical-chemistry/reaction-rate] Reaction rates may also be defined on a basis that is not the volume of the reactor.
[src:physical-chemistry/reaction-rate] When a catalyst is used, the reaction rate may be stated on a catalyst mass [mol/(g⋅s)] or surface area [mol/(m2⋅s)] basis.
[src:physical-chemistry/reaction-rate] If the basis is a specific catalyst site that may be rigorously counted by a specified method, the rate is given in units of s−1 and is called a "turnover frequency".
[src:physical-chemistry/reaction-rate] Factors that influence the reaction rate are the nature of the reaction, concentration, pressure, reaction order, temperature, solvent, electromagnetic radiation, catalyst, isotopes, surface area, stirring, and diffusion limit.
[src:physical-chemistry/reaction-rate] Some reactions are naturally faster than others.
[src:physical-chemistry/reaction-rate] The number of reacting species, their physical state (the particles that form solids move much more slowly than those of gases or those in solution), the complexity of the reaction and other factors can greatly influence the rate of a reaction.
[src:physical-chemistry/reaction-rate] Reaction rate increases with concentration, as described by the rate law and explained by collision theory.
[src:physical-chemistry/reaction-rate] As reactant concentration increases, the frequency of collision increases.
[src:physical-chemistry/reaction-rate] The rate of gaseous reactions increases with pressure, which is, in fact, equivalent to an increase in the concentration of the gas.
[src:physical-chemistry/reaction-rate] The reaction rate increases in the direction where there are fewer moles of gas and decreases in the reverse direction.
[src:physical-chemistry/reaction-rate] For condensed-phase reactions, the pressure dependence is weak.
[src:physical-chemistry/reaction-rate] The order of the reaction controls how the reactant concentration (or pressure) affects the reaction rate.
[src:physical-chemistry/reaction-rate] Usually conducting a reaction at a higher temperature delivers more energy into the system and increases the reaction rate by causing more collisions between particles, as explained by collision theory.
[src:physical-chemistry/reaction-rate] However, the main reason that temperature increases the rate of reaction is that more of the colliding particles will have the necessary activation energy resulting in more successful collisions (when bonds are formed between reactants).
[src:physical-chemistry/reaction-rate] The influence of temperature is described by the Arrhenius equation.
[src:physical-chemistry/reaction-rate] For example, coal burns in a fireplace in the presence of oxygen, but it does not when it is stored at room temperature.
[src:physical-chemistry/reaction-rate] The reaction is spontaneous at low and high temperatures but at room temperature, its rate is so slow that it is negligible.
[src:physical-chemistry/reaction-rate] The increase in temperature, as created by a match, allows the reaction to start and then it heats itself because it is exothermic.
[src:physical-chemistry/reaction-rate] That is valid for many other fuels, such as methane, butane, and hydrogen.
[src:physical-chemistry/reaction-rate] Reaction rates can be independent of temperature (*non-Arrhenius*) or decrease with increasing temperature (*anti-Arrhenius*).
[src:physical-chemistry/reaction-rate] Reactions without an activation barrier (for example, some radical reactions), tend to have anti-Arrhenius temperature dependence: the rate constant decreases with increasing temperature.
[src:physical-chemistry/reaction-rate] Many reactions take place in solution and the properties of the solvent affect the reaction rate.
[src:physical-chemistry/reaction-rate] The ionic strength also has an effect on the reaction rate.
[src:physical-chemistry/reaction-rate] Electromagnetic radiation is a form of energy.
[src:physical-chemistry/reaction-rate] As such, it may speed up the rate or even make a reaction spontaneous as it provides the particles of the reactants with more energy.
[src:physical-chemistry/reaction-rate] This energy is in one way or another stored in the reacting particles (it may break bonds, and promote molecules to electronically or vibrationally excited states...) creating intermediate species that react easily.
[src:physical-chemistry/reaction-rate] As the intensity of light increases, the particles absorb more energy and hence the rate of reaction increases.
[src:physical-chemistry/reaction-rate] For example, when methane reacts with chlorine in the dark, the reaction rate is slow.
[src:physical-chemistry/reaction-rate] It can be sped up when the mixture is put under diffused light.
[src:physical-chemistry/reaction-rate] In bright sunlight, the reaction is explosive.
[src:physical-chemistry/reaction-rate] The presence of a catalyst increases the reaction rate (in both the forward and reverse reactions) by providing an alternative pathway with a lower activation energy.
[src:physical-chemistry/reaction-rate] For example, platinum catalyzes the combustion of hydrogen with oxygen at room temperature.
[src:physical-chemistry/reaction-rate] The kinetic isotope effect consists of a different reaction rate for the same molecule if it has different isotopes, usually hydrogen isotopes, because of the relative mass difference between hydrogen and deuterium.
[src:physical-chemistry/reaction-rate] In reactions on surfaces, which take place, for example, during heterogeneous catalysis, the rate of reaction increases as the surface area does.
[src:physical-chemistry/reaction-rate] That is because more particles of the solid are exposed and can be hit by reactant molecules.
[src:physical-chemistry/reaction-rate] Stirring can have a strong effect on the rate of reaction for heterogeneous reactions.
[src:physical-chemistry/reaction-rate] Some reactions are limited by diffusion.
[src:physical-chemistry/reaction-rate] All the factors that affect a reaction rate, except for concentration and reaction order, are taken into account in the reaction rate coefficient (the coefficient in the rate equation of the reaction).
[src:physical-chemistry/reaction-rate] For a chemical reaction *a*A + *b*B → *p*P + *q*Q, the rate equation or rate law is a mathematical expression used in chemical kinetics to link the rate of a reaction to the concentration of each reactant.
[src:physical-chemistry/reaction-rate] For gas phase reaction the rate equation is often alternatively expressed in terms of partial pressures.
[src:physical-chemistry/reaction-rate] In these equations *k*(*T*) is the *reaction rate coefficient* or *rate constant*, although it is not really a constant, because it includes all the parameters that affect reaction rate, except for time and concentration.
[src:physical-chemistry/reaction-rate] Of all the parameters influencing reaction rates, temperature is normally the most important one and is accounted for by the Arrhenius equation.
[src:physical-chemistry/reaction-rate] The exponents n and m are called reaction orders and depend on the reaction mechanism.
[src:physical-chemistry/reaction-rate] For an elementary (single-step) reaction, the order with respect to each reactant is equal to its stoichiometric coefficient.
[src:physical-chemistry/reaction-rate] For complex (multistep) reactions, however, this is often not true and the rate equation is determined by the detailed mechanism, as illustrated below for the reaction of H2 and NO.
[src:physical-chemistry/reaction-rate] For elementary reactions or reaction steps, the order and stoichiometric coefficient are both equal to the molecularity or number of molecules participating.
[src:physical-chemistry/reaction-rate] For a unimolecular reaction or step, the rate is proportional to the concentration of molecules of reactant, so the rate law is first order.
[src:physical-chemistry/reaction-rate] For a bimolecular reaction or step, the number of collisions is proportional to the product of the two reactant concentrations, or second order.
[src:physical-chemistry/reaction-rate] A termolecular step is predicted to be third order, but also very slow as simultaneous collisions of three molecules are rare.
[src:physical-chemistry/reaction-rate] By using the mass balance for the system in which the reaction occurs, an expression for the rate of change in concentration can be derived.
[src:physical-chemistry/reaction-rate] As for many reactions, the experimental rate equation does not simply reflect the stoichiometric coefficients in the overall reaction: It is third order overall: first order in H2 and second order in NO, even though the stoichiometric coefficients of both reactants are equal to 2.
[src:physical-chemistry/reaction-rate] In chemical kinetics, the overall reaction rate is often explained using a mechanism consisting of a number of elementary steps.
[src:physical-chemistry/reaction-rate] Not all of these steps affect the rate of reaction; normally the slowest elementary step controls the reaction rate.
[src:physical-chemistry/reaction-rate] Reactions 1 and 3 are very rapid compared to the second, so the slow reaction 2 is the rate-determining step.
[src:physical-chemistry/reaction-rate] This is a bimolecular elementary reaction whose rate is given by the second-order equation $v=k_{2}[{\ce {H2}}][{\ce {N2O2}}],$ where *k*2 is the rate constant for the second step.
[src:physical-chemistry/reaction-rate] However N2O2 is an unstable intermediate whose concentration is determined by the fact that the first step is in equilibrium, so that ${\ce {[N2O2]={\mathit {K}}_{1}[NO]^{2}}},$ where *K*1 is the equilibrium constant of the first step.
[src:physical-chemistry/reaction-rate] This agrees with the form of the observed rate equation if it is assumed that *k* = *k*2*K*1.
[src:physical-chemistry/reaction-rate] In practice the rate equation is used to suggest possible mechanisms which predict a rate equation in agreement with experiment.
[src:physical-chemistry/reaction-rate] The second molecule of H2 does not appear in the rate equation because it reacts in the third step, which is a rapid step *after* the rate-determining step, so that it does not affect the overall reaction rate.
[src:physical-chemistry/reaction-rate] Since at temperature T the molecules have energies given by a Boltzmann distribution, one can expect the number of collisions with energy greater than *E*a to be proportional to $\exp \left({\tfrac {-E_{\text{a}}}{RT}}\right)$ .
[src:physical-chemistry/reaction-rate] The values for A and *E*a are dependent on the reaction.
[src:physical-chemistry/reaction-rate] There are also more complex equations possible, which describe the temperature dependence of other rate constants that do not follow this pattern.
[src:physical-chemistry/reaction-rate] Temperature is a measure of the average kinetic energy of the reactants.
[src:physical-chemistry/reaction-rate] As temperature increases, the kinetic energy of the reactants increases.
[src:physical-chemistry/reaction-rate] That is, the particles move faster, which allows more collisions to take place and at a greater speed, so the chance of reactants forming into products increases, which in turn results in the rate of reaction increasing.
[src:physical-chemistry/reaction-rate] As a rule of thumb, a rise of ten degrees Celsius results in approximately twice the reaction rate constant.
[src:physical-chemistry/reaction-rate] The minimum kinetic energy required for a reaction to occur is called the activation energy and is denoted by *E*a or Δ*G*‡.
[src:physical-chemistry/reaction-rate] The transition state or activated complex shown on the diagram is the energy barrier that must be overcome when changing reactants into products.
[src:physical-chemistry/reaction-rate] The molecules with an energy greater than this barrier have enough energy to react.
[src:physical-chemistry/reaction-rate] For a successful collision to take place, the collision geometry must be right, meaning the reactant molecules must face the right way, so the activated complex can be formed.
[src:physical-chemistry/reaction-rate] A chemical reaction takes place only when the reacting particles collide.
[src:physical-chemistry/reaction-rate] However, not all collisions are effective in causing the reaction.
[src:physical-chemistry/reaction-rate] Products are formed only when the colliding particles possess a certain minimum energy called threshold energy.
[src:physical-chemistry/reaction-rate] For a given reaction, the ratio of its rate constant at a higher temperature to its rate constant at a lower temperature is known as its temperature coefficient (Q).
[src:physical-chemistry/reaction-rate] *Q*10 is commonly used as the ratio of rate constants that are 10 °C apart and is usually on the order of 2.
[src:physical-chemistry/reaction-rate] The pressure dependence of the rate constant for condensed-phase reactions (that is, when reactants and products are solids or liquid) is usually sufficiently weak in the range of pressures normally encountered in industry that it is neglected in practice.
[src:physical-chemistry/reaction-rate] The pressure dependence of the rate constant is associated with the activation volume.
[src:physical-chemistry/reaction-rate] Reactions can increase or decrease their rates with pressure, depending on the value of Δ*V* ‡.
[src:physical-chemistry/reaction-rate] As an example of the possible magnitude of the pressure effect, some organic reactions were shown to double the reaction rate when the pressure was increased from atmospheric (0.1 MPa) to 50 MPa (which gives Δ*V* ‡ = −0.025 L/mol).
